 name from a farmhouse so called, once inhabited by a certain <i>Hesso</i> and his kin."]},{"name":"Hessen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erna.  Scandinavian Hjalmer.","German:","habitational name for someone from the territory of Hesse (German <i>Hessen</i>), a region (present-day federal state) in Germany named with the German dative plural form of the name of its inhabitants, the Hessians. Compare   Hess   1."]},{"name":"Hoss","meanings":["German (<b>Höss</b>): variant of   Hess  .","German: dialect variant of   Hose  ."]},{"name":"Hessel","meanings":["German and Dutch: from a pet form of   Hess   3.","German: habitational name from any of the places called Hessel or Hesseln.","Swedish: variant of   Hassel  ."]},{"name":"Hessman","meanings":["Americanized form of German <b>Hessmann</b>:","nickname or occupational name for a chaser at a hunt, from Middle High German <i>hessen</i> ‘to hunt with hounds’.","from a derivative of the personal name <i>Hesso</i> (see   Hess   3)."]},{"name":"Hesse","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Kurt, Hans, Erwin, Florian, Otto, Siegfried, Ullrich, Wilhelm, Wolfgang, Bernd, Bernhard.","German and Dutch: variant of   Hess  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaretha","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margaret","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]},{"name":"Margarete","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margrethe","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1353606,"age":1,"year":"1499","julianDay":2268559,"description":"Swiss forces defeated the forces of the Holy Roman Empire. Switzerland won its complete independence from the empire.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1353607,"age":38,"year":"1536","julianDay":2282072,"description":"Switzerland is a loose confederacy of 13 cities and small valley communities dominating the rest of the country. A few families control state affairs. Several rebellions put down by military force: repressed aspects of history in a country so proud of it's tradition of democracy.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Margaretha Hess was born about 1498, in Zug, Zug, Switzerland. She had at least 2 sons and 3 daughters with Hans Michael Spilmann."},"et":{"abt1498–":"umbes 1498–Surnud","1496–Male":"1496–Surnud","1520–Female":"1520–Surnud","1521–Male":"1521–Surnud","1522–Male":"1522–Surnud","1523–Female":"1523–Surnud","1538–Female":"1538–Surnud","1498–Female":"1498–Surnud","abt1498":"umbes 1498","abt1520":"umbes 1520","abt1522":"umbes 1522","abt1523":"umbes 1523","abt1538":"umbes 1538","abt 1521":"umbes 1521","1536":"1536","1523":"1523","1522":"1522","1499":"1499","1521":"1521","1498":"1498","1520":"1520","1496":"1496","1538":"1538","of Zug, Zug, Switz.":"Zug, Zug, Šveits","Zug, Zug, Switz.":"Zug